## 1. JOINs

Combines rows from two or more tables based on a related column.

### INNER JOIN
Returns only rows that **match in both tables**.

```sql
SELECT employees.name, departments.dept_name
FROM employees
INNER JOIN departments ON employees.dept_id = departments.dept_id;
```
> Frank (no department) won't appear — no match, no row.

---

### LEFT JOIN
Returns **all rows from left table** + matched rows from right (NULL if no match).

```sql
SELECT employees.name, departments.dept_name
FROM employees
LEFT JOIN departments ON employees.dept_id = departments.dept_id;
```
> Frank appears with NULL as department.

---

### RIGHT JOIN
Returns **all rows from right table** + matched rows from left.

```sql
SELECT employees.name, departments.dept_name
FROM employees
RIGHT JOIN departments ON employees.dept_id = departments.dept_id;
```
> Finance (no employees) appears with NULL as employee.

---

### SELF JOIN
A table **joined with itself**. Useful for hierarchical data like managers.

```sql
SELECT e.name AS employee, m.name AS manager
FROM employees e
LEFT JOIN employees m ON e.manager_id = m.emp_id;
```

---

### CROSS JOIN
Every row from Table A paired with every row from Table B.

```sql
SELECT employees.name, departments.dept_name
FROM employees
CROSS JOIN departments;
-- 6 employees × 4 departments = 24 rows
```

---

## 2. UNION

Combines results of two SELECT statements into one.

### UNION — removes duplicates
```sql
SELECT name FROM employees WHERE salary > 80000
UNION
SELECT name FROM employees WHERE dept_id = 1;
```

### UNION ALL — keeps duplicates (faster)
```sql
SELECT name FROM employees WHERE salary > 80000
UNION ALL
SELECT name FROM employees WHERE dept_id = 1;
```

> **Rule:** Both SELECTs must have the same number of columns.

---

## 3. Nested Queries (Subqueries)

A query inside another query. Inner query runs first.

### Subquery in WHERE
```sql
-- Employees earning more than average salary
SELECT name, salary
FROM employees
WHERE salary > (SELECT AVG(salary) FROM employees);
```

---

### Subquery with IN
```sql
-- Employees in the same department as Charlie
SELECT name FROM employees
WHERE dept_id IN (
    SELECT dept_id FROM employees WHERE name = 'Charlie'
);
```

---

### Subquery in FROM (Derived Table)
Treats inner query result as a temporary table.

```sql
SELECT dept_name, avg_salary
FROM (
    SELECT d.dept_name, AVG(e.salary) AS avg_salary
    FROM employees e
    JOIN departments d ON e.dept_id = d.dept_id
    GROUP BY d.dept_name
) AS dept_avg
WHERE avg_salary > 70000;
```

---

### EXISTS
Returns rows where the subquery finds **at least one match**.

```sql
-- Departments that have employees
SELECT dept_name FROM departments d
WHERE EXISTS (
    SELECT 1 FROM employees e WHERE e.dept_id = d.dept_id
);
```

---

## Quick Reference

| Concept | What it does |
|---|---|
| INNER JOIN | Only matching rows from both tables |
| LEFT JOIN | All left rows + matched right |
| RIGHT JOIN | All right rows + matched left |
| SELF JOIN | Table joined with itself |
| CROSS JOIN | Every combination of both tables |
| UNION | Combine results, remove duplicates |
| UNION ALL | Combine results, keep duplicates |
| Subquery in WHERE | Filter using a computed value |
| Subquery in FROM | Use query result as a temp table |
| EXISTS | Check if any matching row exists |

